RMarkdown

image

  • R Markdown at its core is a combination of R and Markdown used to generate reproducible reports for data analyses.
  • R Markdown provides an authoring framework for data science.
  • You can use a single R Markdown file to
    • save and execute code
    • generate high quality reports that can be shared with an audience

Rmarkdown

  • Markdown and R are mixed together in a .Rmd file, which can then be rendered into a number of formats including .html, .pdf, and .docx.
  • Fully reproducible reports
    • Have code, results, and text in the same document
    • Results are generated from the source code, and your documents are automatically updated if your data changed.

Markdown

  • R Markdown is based on markdown, a markup language that that you can use to add formatting elements to plaintext text documents.

  • Markdown is a lightweight and easy-to-use syntax that is widely used to generate HTML pages and for styling the writing on the GitHub platform.

  • It was created by John Gruber in 2004 and it is now one of the world’s most popular markup languages.

  • We go through basic markdown syntax together, and you can learn more at:

    • Markdown Tutorial
    • Mastering Markdown GitHub Guides
    • Markdown Guide

Headers and Quotes

Headers

Headers are created by preceeding the line with a (#) sign. There are six levels. Each level has one more (#) sign than the preceeding level.

# The largest heading
## The second largest heading
###### The smallest heading

Quoting text

Texts are coding by preceeding the line with a (>) sign.

I love MATH 4730!

Quoting code

A code or command within a sentence can be called with by wrapping the code in a single backtick (`).

Use git status to list all new or modified files that haven’t yet been committed.
Triple backticks (```) are used as wrappers when a block of code is required.

The following code will be contained in a block.  
git add    
git commit  
git status

Link

Inline Links

To create an inline link, wrap the link text in brackets ([ ]), followed immediately by the link (href) in parentheses (()).
Google link

Auto Linking

Any valid URL found within the text will automatically be converted to a clickable link.
Putting the url of google https://www.google.com here.

Anchor Links

You can create an anchor link for a header or list item by ending the link with curly braces ({}) enclosing a hash mark (#) followed by the link id.

Header with ID
  • List item 1 with ID {#listid1}
  • List item 2 with ID {#listid2}

Create a link to : Inline Links

List

Unordered Lists

To create an unordered list, put each list item on a separate line, and precede each list item with either an asterisk (*) or a dash (-).

  • You do not need any header before the beginning of the list items.

  • You do not need a blank line before the first list item (though it may help readability).

  • item 1.

  • item 2.

    • sub item 1
    • sub item 2
Ordered Lists

To create an ordered list, put each list item on a separate line, and precede each list item with a number.

  1. You do not need any header before the beginning of the list items.
  2. You do not need a blank line before the first list item (though it may help readability).
  3. The numbers you place at the beginning of each list item do not matter; the list will automatically be re-numbered starting with the first list item.
  4. item 1.
  5. item 2.
Nested Lists

You can create a nested list by indenting one or more list items below another item.

  1. First list item
    • First nested list item
      • Second nested list item

Maths & Tables

Maths

  • inline-maths : To format an inline math code, wrap the math code with the ($) symbol.
    • \(A= \pi r^2\).
  • math-block : To format a block of math code, wrap the code with double ($$) symbol.
    • \[A= \pi r^2. \]

Adding R

  • The real power of RMarkdown comes when we add R.
  • There are two ways we can do this. We can use R code chunks, or run R inline.

R Chunks

The following is an example of an R code chunk

# define function
get_sd <- function(x, biased = TRUE) {
  n = length(x) - 1 * !biased
  sqrt((1 / n) * sum((x - mean(x)) ^ 2))
}


# run function on randomly generated data
set.seed(42)
get_sd(rnorm(n = 10, mean = 2, sd = 5))
  • Notice the syntax that creates and ends the chunk.
  • Note that example_chunk is the chunk name.
  • Everything between the start and end syntax must be valid R code.
  • Chunk names are not necessary, but can become useful as your documents grow in size.
  • In this example, we define a function, generate some random data in a reproducible manner, then ran our function.

Inline R

R can also be ran in the middle of exposition. For example, the sum of 3 and 7 is 10.

Adding Math with LaTeX

  • RMarkdown is the ability to add Latex for mathematics typesetting.
  • There are two ways we can include Latex; displaystyle and inline.
  • Note that use of LaTeX is somewhat dependent on the resulting file format. For example, it cannot be used at all with .docx. - To use it with .pdf you must have LaTeX install on your machine.
  • With .html the LaTeX is not actually rendered during knitting, but actually rendered in your browser using MathJax.

Displaystyle LaTeX

Displaystyle is used for larger equations which appear centered on their own line.

\[
s = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n - 1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x - \bar{x})^2}
\]

\[ s = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n - 1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x - \bar{x})^2} \]

Inline LaTex

We could mix LaTeX commands in the middle of exposition, for example: $t = 2$ \(t = 2\). We could actually mix R with Latex as well! For example: $\bar{x} =3.5$ \(\bar{x} = 3.5\).

Output Options

  • At the beginning of the document, there is code which describes some metadata and settings of the document.
  • For this file, that code is:
---
title: "RMarkdown Template"
author: "Your Name and Section"
date: ""
output: 
  html_document: 
    theme: readable
    toc: yes
---
  • This describes the output format as html, defines the theme.
  • toc tells R to automatically create a Table of Contents based on the headers and sub-headers you have defined using #.
  • You can edit this yourself, or click the settings button at the top of the document and select Output Options....
  • You can explore other themes and syntax highlighting options, as well as many additional options.
